<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="35" type="etymology">
<paragraph pageId="2" pageNumber="35">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="2" pageNumber="35">
Latin adjective 
<taxonomicName lsidName="angustus" pageId="2" pageNumber="35" rank="species" species="angustus">angustus</taxonomicName>
, meaning narrow. This is the most elongated species in the genus in the Afrotropical region.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="35" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="2" pageNumber="35">Distribution and biology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="2" pageNumber="35">
Only known from the type locality. It was taken together with 
<taxonomicName genus="M." lsidName="M. camerunus" pageId="2" pageNumber="35" rank="species" species="camerunus">M. camerunus</taxonomicName>
(Eggers, 1919) under thick bark of a fallen 
<taxonomicName class="Gastropoda" family="Ficidae" genus="Ficus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Ficus" order="Littorinimorpha" pageId="2" pageNumber="35" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">Ficus</taxonomicName>
tree. Both species used entrance holes made by 
<taxonomicName class="Lecanoromycetes" family="Stereocaulaceae" genus="Xyleborus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Xyleborus principalis" order="Lecanorales" pageId="2" pageNumber="35" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="principalis">Xyleborus principalis</taxonomicName>
Eichhoff, 1878.
</paragraph>
